sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE TOP SPOT AFTER INNINGS WIN.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the County Championship.

However, their lead could be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey are all on the verge of victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling out Somerset by 83 runs on the first morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296. Andy Caddick, who was dropped from England, scored three runs for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset got off to a solid start in the second innings before Simmons brought them to their knees with 174.
However, Essex look certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such kept a firm grip on the game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to requirements for England's one-dayers, struck 158, his first championship hundred of the season, as Essex scored 372 and led by 82 in their first innings.

By the close, Yorkshire had turned that lead into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes by conceding four for 24 in 48 balls, leaving the side hanging at 119 for five as they prayed for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another England dismissal, silenced his critics when he followed up his four points for 45 on Thursday by scoring 80 without conceding in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points to leave Surrey with a final score of 429, 234 points ahead.

Derbyshire kept up their chase for a first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings and were still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australian Tom Moody scored six for 82 but Chris Adams (123) and Tim O'Gorman (109) took Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the disappointment of the first day's play being affected by the weather, Kent stepped up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire with 214 points.
They were held in check by Paul Johnson's 84, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
At the close of play, Kent had reached 108 for three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER BECOMES CAPTAIN OF ENGLAND.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15m ($23.4m), replaces Tony Adams, who led the side during June's European Championship, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes over as captain on a trial basis but new coach Glenn Hoddle sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton skipper should not make the job his own.
"I'm sure there will be no problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan he was ready and really wanted to do it.
"It is very difficult to come to a 100 per cent result in four days....
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him, and he knows about the situation in the team, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's strike partner at Euro 96, Teddy Sheringham, was ruled out of the squad on Friday with an injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle team-mate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUT AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players in Saturday's 1-0 home defeat, ending their brief spell at the top of the table.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary commission, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play in front of empty seats against Lada Togliatti on 3 September.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is well-placed in the championship with 11 games still to play.
Volgograd are three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, but have one game more than the league leaders and two more than the Moscow club.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN FROM PANAMA FIGHTS AGAINST THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran climbs into the ring on Saturday for another attempt to extend his long career.
Duran, 45, takes on little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The fight, Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is billed here as the "return of the legend" and Duran still speaks as if he is in his prime.
This fight is to prepare me.
I will not retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the greatest boxers in the world," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Federation.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho had taken a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO AND O'BRIEN PROVIDE TWO SURPRISES UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of surprises at the U.S. Open.
Washington, seeded 11th, failed to repeat his Wimbledon miracle comeback as he lost 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 3-6, 6-3 to red-hot wildcard Alex O'Brien in a two-hour, 51-minute battle on Stadium Court.
Next door in the stands, 10th seed Rios lost to another Wimbledon-bound player - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The spirited left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although former champion Agassi, seeded sixth, had to wriggle out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole by winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the evening belonged to the upstarts.
Washington, who came back from 1-5 down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title a fortnight ago in New Haven, served for 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back.
"I kept telling myself, 'Give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen'," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself because normally I would have broken down the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former US college champion, hit 17 aces to defeat the never-say-die Washington.
The fifth set remained thrilling until the sixth game, when Washington fought off a break point with a forehand winner down the line and netted a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point to win when Washington hit another backhand into the net for 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and try to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense at some moments," Washington said.
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a ban from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued with Rios in the stands with phone calls and taunted fans in his lively tango that lasted two hours and 24 minutes.
A raucous cheering section supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who drew all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said the 104th-ranked Tarango. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was only decided in the tiebreak of the third set, which the American won 7:5 to the horror of the spectators.
"I love the audience when they boo me every day.
It spurs me on and makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played my best tennis in college when the fraternities were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would enjoy it a lot more. "
Rios was not amused by Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's it.
I think I played really badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were flying really fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play an American, so I also play at night.
I didn't feel comfortable on the pitch. "
At the end of the fight, Tarango threw sarcastic kisses to the crowd and then wiggled his body to a Rios cheering group.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they blatantly cheer me on.
After I won, I figured I could mix it up a bit. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RESIGNS.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's best rusher at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever used at the centre position, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham was selected to the Pro Bowl three times and rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I am sad to leave, I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on hold for some time.
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was the cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Cunningham, a second-round pick in 1985, completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been hired as a broadcaster.
